## Conditional rendering: show this or that

In HTML, what you write is what appears. In React, components can **decide** what to show based on data. This is called conditional rendering, and it uses two JavaScript patterns you will see everywhere in React codebases.

### Pattern 1: The ternary operator

The ternary operator is a one-line if/else. The syntax is:

```
condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse
```

In React, it looks like this:

```jsx
function LoginStatus({ isLoggedIn, userName }) {
  return (
    <div className="auth-status">
      {isLoggedIn ? (
        <span>Welcome back, {userName}</span>
      ) : (
        <span>Please sign in</span>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Read it as: "If `isLoggedIn` is true, show 'Welcome back, [name]'. Otherwise, show 'Please sign in.'"

When used as `<LoginStatus isLoggedIn={true} userName="Alex" />`, the user sees: **Welcome back, Alex**.
When used as `<LoginStatus isLoggedIn={false} userName="Alex" />`, the user sees: **Please sign in**.

The ternary is the most common conditional pattern in React because it fits naturally inside JSX curly braces. Here are more examples:

```jsx
// Show different text
<p>{items.length > 0 ? `${items.length} results` : "No results found"}</p>

// Show different components
{isPremium ? <PremiumBadge /> : <FreeBadge />}

// Show different CSS classes
<button className={isActive ? "btn btn-primary" : "btn btn-secondary"}>
  {isActive ? "Active" : "Inactive"}
</button>
```

The ternary always has two branches: the true case and the false case. Both branches must produce something (text, JSX, or `null` to show nothing).

### Pattern 2: The `&&` (AND) short-circuit

Sometimes you want to show something or show nothing -- there is no "else" case. For this, React developers use the `&&` operator:

```jsx
function UserProfile({ name, isAdmin }) {
  return (
    <div className="profile">
      <h2>{name}</h2>
      {isAdmin && <span className="admin-badge">Admin</span>}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Read `{isAdmin && <span>Admin</span>}` as: "If isAdmin is true, show the Admin badge. Otherwise, show nothing."

This works because of how JavaScript evaluates `&&`. If the left side is false, JavaScript stops and returns nothing (which React renders as blank space). If the left side is true, JavaScript returns the right side (the JSX).

Common uses of the `&&` pattern:

```jsx
// Show a section only for admins
{isAdmin && <AdminPanel />}

// Show an error message only when there is an error
{error && <p className="error">{error}</p>}

// Show a loading indicator
{isLoading && <Spinner />}

// Show a notification count only when there are notifications
{notifications.length > 0 && (
  <span className="badge">{notifications.length}</span>
)}
```

### The `&&` gotcha: zero renders as text

There is one important trap with `&&` that catches even experienced developers:

```jsx
function ItemCount({ count }) {
  return (
    <div>
      {count && <p>You have {count} items</p>}
    </div>
  );
}
```

When `count` is 5, this shows: **You have 5 items**. Good.
When `count` is 0, you might expect it to show nothing. Instead, it shows: **0**.

Why? In JavaScript, `0` is "falsy," so `&&` returns the left side (`0`). React renders `0` as the text "0" because it is a valid number. The fix is to explicitly check for the condition:

```jsx
// Fix: explicitly check for > 0
{count > 0 && <p>You have {count} items</p>}
```

This is a common bug in React code and a common mistake in AI-generated code. When you see `{someNumber && ...}`, check whether the number could be zero.

### Conditional CSS classes

Conditional rendering is not just about showing and hiding elements -- it is also used to change how things look:

```jsx
function Tab({ label, isActive }) {
  return (
    <button className={isActive ? "tab active" : "tab"}>
      {label}
    </button>
  );
}
```

When `isActive` is true, the button gets the classes "tab active". When false, just "tab". This is how React components change their appearance based on state or props -- by swapping CSS classes.

You will also see the template literal style:

```jsx
<div className={`card ${isHighlighted ? "highlighted" : ""}`}>
```

This always applies the "card" class and conditionally adds "highlighted".

### A realistic example: notification center

Here is a component that combines multiple conditional rendering patterns:

```jsx
function NotificationCenter({ notifications, isOpen }) {
  const unreadCount = notifications.filter(n => !n.read).length;

  return (
    <div className="notification-center">
      <button className="notification-bell">
        Notifications
        {unreadCount > 0 && (
          <span className="badge">{unreadCount}</span>
        )}
      </button>

      {isOpen && (
        <div className="notification-panel">
          {notifications.length > 0 ? (
            <ul>
              {notifications.map(n => (
                <li key={n.id} className={n.read ? "read" : "unread"}>
                  {n.message}
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          ) : (
            <p className="empty">No notifications</p>
          )}
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Let us read each conditional:

1. `{unreadCount > 0 && <span className="badge">{unreadCount}</span>}` -- Show the count badge only when there are unread notifications. Uses `> 0` to avoid the zero gotcha.

2. `{isOpen && <div className="notification-panel">...}` -- Show the notification panel only when isOpen is true.

3. `{notifications.length > 0 ? <ul>... : <p>No notifications</p>}` -- If there are notifications, show them as a list. Otherwise, show an empty state message.

4. `className={n.read ? "read" : "unread"}` -- Apply different CSS classes based on whether each notification has been read.

Notice how conditions nest: the panel only shows when open, and inside the panel, the content changes based on whether there are notifications. This is typical of real React code.

